I. TERMINOLOGY- WHAT DO WE MEAN?<br><br>
I think we need to make sure we are using the same terminology if we are ever going to see some resolution to this debate:<br><br>
a)  &quot;Prejudice&quot; strictly defined is an preformed and unsubstantiated judgement about an individual or group.  Although this may be a favorable or unfavorable pre-formed disposition the term most often denotes an unfavorable or hostile attitude toward other people based on their identification as a part of a group.  A prejudiced attitude held by a dominant group against a minority or disadvantaged group within the same society may result in discrimination.<br><br>
b)  &quot;Discrimination&quot;  a situation in which a group or individual of the perceived group is treated differently.  Examples of groupings include disability, ethnicity, religion, sex, and age. The discrimination may be beneficial to the person but more likely it is not.<br><br>
c)  &quot;Racism&quot; makes the race of other people as a discerning factor in attitudes of actions about them.  The term implies a superiority of ones own race.  <br><br>
On this thread we have seen a variety of attitudes to Lien's question. &quot;What are We?&quot;  Her first post contained nothing inflammatory all she did was not give her e-mail address. ( That alone always gets Dr. Spatz stirred up.)   She received very different responses; some showed acceptance, some showed prejudice based upon the fact that she indicated she is Vietnamese.  In subsequent posts there have been allusions to subtle and overt discrimination, and racism toward the Vietnamese by some Vets and non-vets alike..<br><br>
II.  Dr. Barry Spatz is a big fan of process.  So lets organize some of the process which has transpired to date. <br><br>
A.  DOC DEL<br><br>
1. DocDel comes to this discussion with his own set of baggage.  He had a daughter who was buried in a cemetery on Hawaii which was vandalized by a mainland hate group .  His favorable comments about other Asians and defense of Lien on this thread resulted in angry/vicious mail.   Another daughter (Patti) who is Korean picked up mail to Dad which contained  racially motivated derogatory statements.<br><br>
2.  April 24, 1997 DocDel says &quot;I stand up for what I believe is right, I stand up against tyrannical treatment, I stand up to bullies.&quot;  He explained that he had to stand up to six different men who contacted him to justify their reason for prejudice, discrimination and being a racist. <br>
Barry, is a handy target because he is online with the discussion. The other 6 aren't. <br><br>
3.  Doc Del's  told Barry &quot; I really wanted you to be able to drive down that highway/freeway and to be able to see that &quot;Little Saigon&quot; sign in a different light and to feel OK about it. Nothing more.&quot; 4/24/97 <br><br>
B.  OTHER POSTERS<br><br>
1.   Gerald &quot;Professor&quot; pointed out that experiences with Vietnamese Interpreters assigned to the intelligence company ranged from good to indifferent as soldiers recognizing that race isn't the determinor in what someone is.  If we all came out of Vietnam experience with a common &quot;mad-on&quot; for all Vietnamese, then that would be an evil legacy. <br><br>
2.  Searat (John Ratliff) said &quot;One of the biggest obstacles to peace and harmonious living is racist attitudes, and those individuals who harbor these kind of attitudes need to be confronted concerning them. ... It is my belief that your (Vietnamese peoples ) presence in the USA does bring back bad memories, and not only to Vietnam Veterans.  Your presence, and the &quot;Little Saigon&quot; sign, is tangible evidence that the ideals that the protestors espoused were hollow.&quot;   In a later post John continued &quot;Hate is hate is hate, and it matters little whether there is an act of malicious violation of hallowed ground or simple words. &quot;  <br><br>
3. Chet Botkins 4/25/97 stated &quot; the Vietnamese people are not the cause for us being where we are today.  They are easy targets.  BUT THEY ARE NOT THE CAUSE !!Everybody get that?....When I was in turmoil,  I lived only 5 miles from the largest concentration of Vietnamese in the US today.  It was bitterness and envy to see them doing so well.  To be incorporated into a life that I was still on the outside of. ..... The horror stories that I heard when I finally listened made me feel ashamed.&quot;<br><br>
Tom and Gerry had similar comments.<br><br>
C. DR. BARRY SPATZ<br><br>
1.  Barry had a negative experience with an ex-neighbor who was a former Capt. in the RVN which he generalized to all Vietnamese.  4/23/97  he says you say you are sick and get big dollars.   Justification - Realist or racist.  Superiority moving from prejudice, to racial discrimination.   Thin lines between where one falls on the scale of racism.   <br><br>
2.  4/24/97 Dr. recognizes he used  personal incident for more global occurrence and apologizes. Is that because he really is penitent?  (I realize that I am sounding like a racist redneck, which I am not, and I am basing my views of a weird sample of the population, not probably true of the whole, but it is all I have, but God Dam, Doc Del, I had to vent it.) <br><br>
3.  Later on the 24th Dr. Barry says your posts have caused me to rethink my emotions with my ex- neighbor.  It is the guy, not his race that still pisses me off. Lazy thinking.  <br><br>
4.  To Chet Dr. Barry says that if for one moment I thought that my sharing my own mental stumbling would be seen as an encouragement for that slime, I would never have posted.......Hatred comes in all colors, and in all disguises.  Yes, I have hatred too, hatred for those who hate me, hatred for those who slaughtered all my relatives in WW2, and hatred for anyone who wants to F***with any friend of mine.&quot; <br><br>
5.  In Racism, Reality and Onions Dr. Barry thinks further and says &quot;Racism, the topic we all seemed to have flamed on/over, is a very ugly topic and issue, and can take the form of desecrating cemeteries, burning crosses, or more subtle forms, like denying jobs, houses, loans, or even more subtle, holding someone or one group up to a different standard, a different level of thinking.  Be it better or worse, higher or lower, when you think about a group of people in a different manner intellectually, or hold that group to a different level of rules, that too is racism, only very subtle.&quot;<br><br>
**********************************************************************<br><br>
What I have never understood was why one people discriminated against and forced to leave their homeland due to racial, religious, or other reasons would do the same thing to someone else in a new community.  Or, why veterans who have been discriminated against upon their return would do the same thing to their Vietnamese allies.  We want to be respected or judged based upon our own conduct not that of a larger group. Can we learn from our experiences? <br><br>
I believe this was Doc Dels' indignation that Barry who felt strongly enough to volunteer in Israel during the summer of 1967 (the famous 6 day war) would be prejudiced and discriminate against the Vietnamese.  It also seems the PhD doth protest too much me think about the  use of  Vietnamese-American, Jewish-American etc.   Barry you hold to Jewish and American, not just American.  Terrible things happen all over the world but you volunteer only for Israel.  You are American but when your country said we want you.  You said no way, I'd rather shovel shit at home or is it that you have &quot;matured&quot; over the years.<br><br>
JOHN   I am not denying that Barry was/is a racist, but I DO NOT believe he is a &quot;hate crime type of  racist&quot; even if he does get a bit hot under the collar.  In your April 25th post you  state &quot; The things you have posted here are not what you would have posted had you not know Lien's race/national origin.  Had she been born a year or two later (in the USA), identified herself as &quot;Betty&quot; and asked her question in the third person instead of in the first person, your answers would have been much different.  It is important to realize here that Barry has this control thingie about knowing the e-mail address of whoever he is talking to.  Before I ever posted to this dialog area I had written to him at his e-mail address so he knew mine.  Nurse Hand didn't stay long enough or I have no doubt he would have been on her case just like he has been on a number of others for not putting down who and where they are. <br>
 <br>
DOC DEL   April 26  Barry wrote  &quot;The lessons from the Holocaust are that first you demonize people, then you separate them, isolate them, turn them into the scapegoat for all the ill's of your culture or society.&quot;  I believe that part of what he is trying to say about &quot;Little Saigon&quot;  is that it disturbs because here is a group that is living physically separated from the rest of our culture and it reminds him of the yellow stars, and numbers tattoed on arms in Nazi Germany where Jewish people were targetted, and  then distanced from the human race.  Dr. Barry thus wants them out of the enclave and assimilated.  Problem is they will still be an easily identified group because of their appearance, there is no hiding through assimilation.  The Jewish people's assimilation into Germany didn't protect them once they were singled out.  In addition, if this is the choice of where people want to be, it is not the same as being told to pack up all your things, and get on the bus for the concentration camps.<br><br>
BARRY  You indicated that Little Saigon is on the other side of the city, or something like that. Someone else  stated that this is a busling little district.  Are you ready to put aside assumptions, control your emotions, get in your car some weekend and go see for yourself first hand what it is like in Little Saigon.  Who knows you may develop a taste for Nuc Marm. If you can find lychee nuts I hardily recommend them.  Loved the little fruit.  <br><br>
TO THE NOW INFAMOUS SIX, ET AL.<br><br>
I have absolutely no idea what you said to rile up Doc Del.  That is done and in the past.  The question now is what are you going to do in the future.  I know that in Vietnam we couldn't tell who was South Vienamese and friendly from the enemy sympathizers.  We sure stood out.<br><br>
The first reaction to seeing someone Vietnamese , because of the past,  may  be this strange feeling in your gut.  We need to control what is no longer appropriate but instinctual behavior. Remember it is us not necessarily anything &quot;they&quot; are doing.   Self talk yourself down.  There may be a past reason for the reaction but that doesn't mean we should act on it.<br><br>
The thing that saddens me about this reaction, if it is based upon service in Vietnam, is that if anyone is to be thanking you for what you went through over in that country, it is most likely going to be the South Vietnamese who you were fighting alongside with and their families.  The knee jerk reaction to Vietnamese isn't functional anymore.  You might want to read Vu Tang's story at http://www.grunt  He doesn't come out and say thank you but that is what his post ultimately is.  Should we be turning friends into enemies because of racist and prejudiced attitudes?
